**Code Explanation:**

The code performs the final performance assessment and visualization of the trained SR-DAE model. 1. Cross-Correlation Coefficient (r_ell): It evaluates the model on the held-out validation set, applying the inverse soft-clipping transformation to recover the physical tSZ Compton-y maps. It then computes the auto- and cross-power spectra between the predicted and true tSZ maps using utils.powers. The cross-correlation coefficient r_ell is calculated as the ratio of the mean cross-spectrum to the geometric mean of the auto-spectra, quantifying the phase coherence across spatial scales. 2. Bias-Variance Check: It flattens the true and predicted tSZ maps and bins the true tSZ intensities into 10 linearly spaced bins. For each bin, it computes the mean and standard deviation of the residuals (predicted - true), revealing any systematic underestimation in high-density regions or overestimation in low-density regions. 3. Integrated Gradients Saliency Maps: It implements an Integrated Gradients module to generate saliency maps for a representative high-mass cluster (highest peak tSZ) and a low-mass filament (25th percentile peak tSZ). The baseline is set to zeros, which corresponds to the median background due to the robust scaling applied during preprocessing. The saliency maps are normalized by the input variance to ensure gradients reflect informative features rather than numerical magnitude. The mean absolute saliency across the main (SO) and auxiliary (Planck CIB) channels is visualized and saved. 4. Data Saving: All numerical results, including r_ell, bias statistics, and the integrated-Y recovery from the previous step, are saved to a structured .npz file for the researcher agent to synthesize.

**Modifications:**

Added if __name__ == '__main__': block, ensured all paths use data/ directory, removed LaTeX rendering, and fixed string formatting to avoid f-strings where necessary.

